throughout this presentation, starting with communication.

115
00:05:49,064 --> 00:05:51,145
So for those of you who haven't played God of War,

116
00:05:51,185 --> 00:05:53,005
there is a giant snake in our game,

117
00:05:53,245 --> 00:05:54,406
and you have to learn to talk to it.

118
00:05:54,946 --> 00:05:57,107
And Kratos comes up with a very interesting method

119
00:05:57,227 --> 00:05:58,707
of communicating with this snake.

120
00:05:58,727 --> 00:06:00,248
So I thought that was a good example

121
00:06:00,768 --> 00:06:03,589
of figuring out how to get your department running smoothly,

122
00:06:04,049 --> 00:06:05,110
collaborating with your team,

123
00:06:05,670 --> 00:06:07,791
and communicating your needs to other departments.

124
00:06:08,871 --> 00:06:10,231
The first thing I learned as an artist

125
00:06:10,291 --> 00:06:12,032
was how to get out of the groove.

126
00:06:13,147 --> 00:06:15,629
As an artist, it's very easy to shut yourself in the studio,

127
00:06:16,050 --> 00:06:17,811
put your headphones on, keep your head down,

128
00:06:17,831 --> 00:06:19,313
and focus on a task.

129
00:06:19,673 --> 00:06:21,034
This is actually encouraged for artists

130
00:06:21,054 --> 00:06:23,116
because often they need to focus for hours at a time

131
00:06:23,156 --> 00:06:25,178
to get really in the groove and get things done.

132
00:06:26,279 --> 00:06:28,261
But as a lead, you have to be aware

133
00:06:28,301 --> 00:06:30,042
of what your team is doing around you.

134
00:06:31,043 --> 00:06:33,025
So it's time to get those headphones off

135
00:06:33,846 --> 00:06:35,407
and figure out if there's any fires happening.

136
00:06:36,513 --> 00:06:38,614
This may come at the expense of your own focus,

137
00:06:39,134 --> 00:06:40,715
but it does benefit the needs of others

138
00:06:41,155 --> 00:06:43,356
and helps you maintain a big picture of what's going on.

139
00:06:44,096 --> 00:06:46,357
You can better guide your team to do their work well,

140
00:06:46,878 --> 00:06:49,599
such as demonstrating a combat move for your animators.

141
00:06:53,240 --> 00:06:54,781
The next thing I learned is that leads

142
00:06:54,981 --> 00:06:57,703
often need to get away from their desk and visit people.

143
00:06:58,636 --> 00:07:00,758
There are lots of benefits of being in a studio

144
00:07:00,878 --> 00:07:01,838
versus working remotely.

145
00:07:02,339 --> 00:07:03,780
Communication goes more smoothly

146
00:07:03,880 --> 00:07:05,561
when you can see people's facial expressions,

147
00:07:05,601 --> 00:07:07,643
when you can use gestures to demonstrate what you want.

148
00:07:08,644 --> 00:07:10,065
You can have one-on-one conversations

149
00:07:10,105 --> 00:07:11,546
going back and forth with each other.

150
00:07:12,667 --> 00:07:14,869
And sometimes it's easier to demonstrate at someone's desk

151
00:07:15,249 --> 00:07:17,050
than trying to write up a detailed email

152
00:07:17,311 --> 00:07:18,612
with screenshots and all that stuff.

153
00:07:19,672 --> 00:07:20,833
So just get away from your desk.

154
00:07:21,842 --> 00:07:24,043
Now at Santa Monica Studio, this can be kind of difficult

155
00:07:24,103 --> 00:07:25,724
because half of our team is upstairs

156
00:07:26,165 --> 00:07:28,106
and half of our team is way downstairs.

157
00:07:28,886 --> 00:07:30,927
So often people don't want to make the trek

158
00:07:30,967 --> 00:07:32,488
because it's just so far.

159
00:07:32,788 --> 00:07:34,369
Why can't we just use Instant Messenger, right?

160
00:07:35,270 --> 00:07:36,890
But it really is worth it to make the trek.

161
00:07:37,451 --> 00:07:39,312
You get more communication going

162
00:07:39,852 --> 00:07:41,593
and you get a little bit of exercise

163
00:07:41,633 --> 00:07:43,374
and who doesn't need more steps on their Fitbit, right?

164
00:07:46,085 --> 00:07:47,907
Now if you need to talk to a lot of people,

165
00:07:48,087 --> 00:07:49,508
you could run up and down the stairs

166
00:07:49,528 --> 00:07:51,049
going individually to everybody's desk

167
00:07:51,689 --> 00:07:53,190
and hope that they're available and around,

168
00:07:53,891 --> 00:07:55,792
or you could just schedule a meeting with everybody

169
00:07:55,852 --> 00:07:56,633
and get them all together.

170
00:07:57,834 --> 00:08:00,576
The benefits of this are that everybody gets to prep

171
00:08:00,656 --> 00:08:02,197
for the subject that you're going to discuss

172
00:08:02,757 --> 00:08:04,458
and be in that mindset to discuss it.

173
00:08:05,359 --> 00:08:07,641
Plus everybody hears the same thing at the same time

174
00:08:08,081 --> 00:08:09,702
so there's less room for misinterpretation.

175
00:08:10,965 --> 00:08:12,766
On God of War, we tried to group our meetings

176
00:08:12,806 --> 00:08:13,847
to certain days of the week,

177
00:08:13,967 --> 00:08:15,268
such as Tuesdays and Thursdays.

178
00:08:15,968 --> 00:08:17,189
That way, on the other days of the week,

179
00:08:17,229 --> 00:08:19,590
people could stay in the groove and keep their work done.

180
