197
00:09:00,693 --> 00:09:01,573
about point number three.

198
00:09:02,094 --> 00:09:02,935
All right, let's get started.

199
00:09:03,255 --> 00:09:04,676
So what have we learned about communication?

200
00:09:05,610 --> 00:09:06,771
It doesn't have to be scary.

201
00:09:07,151 --> 00:09:09,733
It's as simple as just turning to someone next to you and saying hi.

202
00:09:10,834 --> 00:09:12,996
And if you mess up or stumble a little bit, that's fine.

203
00:09:13,076 --> 00:09:14,817
Messing up is still better than saying nothing.

204
00:09:14,977 --> 00:09:18,460
I mean, we're not mind readers and we won't know what you have to say unless you actually

205
00:09:18,520 --> 00:09:18,781
say it.

206
00:09:18,841 --> 00:09:20,222
So don't bottle it up inside you.

207
00:09:21,303 --> 00:09:22,464
Just keep talking to each other.

208
00:09:23,324 --> 00:09:26,347
One of the worst things that could happen to a team is that communication breaks down

209
00:09:26,427 --> 00:09:29,970
and people just kind of go into their own corners and work on things without communicating

210
00:09:30,010 --> 00:09:30,410
to each other.

211
00:09:30,850 --> 00:09:31,511
So keep talking.

212
00:09:33,225 --> 00:09:36,186
The next concept I'd like to talk about is organization.

213
00:09:36,906 --> 00:09:38,207
This is one of the characters in our game.

214
00:09:38,227 --> 00:09:40,788
He's a shopkeeper, and he loves to keep all his tools

215
00:09:40,828 --> 00:09:42,869
nice and clean and his workshop nice and tidy.

216
00:09:43,909 --> 00:09:46,691
And as a lead, a little bit of OCD can go a long way as well

217
00:09:46,771 --> 00:09:48,992
to getting your team to run like a well-oiled machine.

218
00:09:50,443 --> 00:09:52,544
A big part of organization is time management,

219
00:09:53,065 --> 00:09:55,525
and a big part of time management is getting good estimates.

220
00:09:56,286 --> 00:09:58,467
Now, every artist is asked how long they need

221
00:09:58,487 --> 00:09:59,247
to get their art done.

222
00:09:59,807 --> 00:10:01,008
That wasn't a new concept for me,

223
00:10:01,808 --> 00:10:03,189
but the shell shock was figuring out

224
00:10:03,329 --> 00:10:05,589
how to gauge the speed of all my other team members.

225
00:10:06,410 --> 00:10:08,151
So, you know, you would go to each of their team members

226
00:10:08,171 --> 00:10:10,271
and be like, well, how much time do you need for this task?

227
00:10:11,532 --> 00:10:13,513
But the problem is, you don't wanna pressure them

228
00:10:13,553 --> 00:10:14,913
to give you better numbers,

229
00:10:14,993 --> 00:10:16,934
to try to get them to do their work done faster.

230
00:10:17,354 --> 00:10:19,715
What you're trying to do is get an accurate sense

231
00:10:19,755 --> 00:10:20,215
of how long the.

232
00:10:20,596 --> 00:10:24,438
the time is going to take them because that's going to help you plan out a proper schedule

233
00:10:24,518 --> 00:10:28,359
and figure out how to mitigate crunch if you can avoid it if possible.

234
00:10:30,580 --> 00:10:34,802
Make sure to plan for unknowns and setbacks because you know stuff's going to go wrong

235
00:10:34,842 --> 00:10:35,782
or stuff's going to need to get changed.

236
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:37,323
You're going to have to start over for some things.

237
00:10:38,344 --> 00:10:43,746
I've heard about 20% buffer can be a good rough estimate just to tack on to every task.

238
00:10:45,947 --> 00:10:47,708
And remember that little stuff takes time too.

239
00:10:48,527 --> 00:10:50,549
A very small task that might be a half hour here,

240
00:10:50,829 --> 00:10:52,391
five minutes there, half a day here,

241
00:10:53,091 --> 00:10:55,153
all that stuff can add up over a long production

242
00:10:55,173 --> 00:10:57,255
such as God of War, which took several years.

243
00:10:58,075 --> 00:10:59,977
So if you're not keeping track of that little stuff

244
00:11:00,037 --> 00:11:02,059
and planning for it in your unknowns and your buffers,

245
00:11:02,399 --> 00:11:03,980
then that can come up to bite you later.

246
00:11:05,802 --> 00:11:07,944
Be honest with yourself and with your producers.

247
00:11:08,604 --> 00:11:10,826
If you see that the scope of your work is getting big

248
00:11:10,866 --> 00:11:11,927
and too big for your team,

249
00:11:12,648 --> 00:11:15,850
start having those hard talks about cutting things.

250
00:11:16,307 --> 00:11:17,347
or increasing your head count,

251
00:11:17,907 --> 00:11:19,628
definitely don't fudge the numbers

252
00:11:19,848 --> 00:11:21,629
because you're really only setting up your team

253
00:11:21,669 --> 00:11:23,370
for crunch or for outright failure.

254
00:11:25,872 --> 00:11:27,873
On God of War, we did a pretty good job

255
00:11:28,133 --> 00:11:30,574
of keeping track of our 100 plus cinematics.

256
00:11:31,294 --> 00:11:33,635
And we kept track of all the progress in Shotgun.

257
00:11:33,655 --> 00:11:35,797
We broke down each of the production phases here

258
00:11:35,837 --> 00:11:38,778
and we were able to tag when things were being worked on.

