00:11:40,479 --> 00:11:41,780
What we didn't do such a good job of

260
00:11:42,160 --> 00:11:43,861
was estimating how much time

261
00:11:44,061 --> 00:11:45,361
each of those tasks was going to take.

262
00:11:46,914 --> 00:11:49,297
or how much time it actually took when it was finished.

263
00:11:50,839 --> 00:11:51,179
Yeah.

264
00:11:53,141 --> 00:11:54,904
Where we really failed was in keeping track

265
00:11:54,924 --> 00:11:55,925
of all those little things.

266
00:11:56,506 --> 00:11:57,887
We had a lot of small animations

267
00:11:57,907 --> 00:12:00,190
which we called points of interest, or POIs,

268
00:12:00,731 --> 00:12:02,413
which were not big, full cinematics.

269
00:12:02,573 --> 00:12:03,815
It might have been just a small thing

270
00:12:03,855 --> 00:12:06,098
like Freya constructing a magical bridge right here.

271
00:12:07,111 --> 00:12:10,473
But add everything up together, and it became way bigger,

272
00:12:10,634 --> 00:12:12,255
and it just went way out of scope,

273
00:12:12,375 --> 00:12:14,396
and we ended up having to cut all of these.

274
00:12:14,416 --> 00:12:15,998
You can see we just didn't do them,

275
00:12:16,218 --> 00:12:17,078
and that was pretty sad.

276
00:12:20,701 --> 00:12:24,424
So, we really want to collect data with those estimates.

277
00:12:25,805 --> 00:12:27,786
There's different kinds of tracking software you can use.

278
00:12:27,926 --> 00:12:28,767
We use Shotgun.

279
00:12:29,592 --> 00:12:31,393
You can use Jira, you can use Handsoft,

280
00:12:31,453 --> 00:12:33,174
whatever option works best for your team.

281
00:12:33,955 --> 00:12:36,196
But the trick is just getting everybody to pitch in

282
00:12:36,396 --> 00:12:38,937
and give their estimates and give their actual time spent.

283
00:12:40,678 --> 00:12:42,499
Because real data is going to lead

284
00:12:42,519 --> 00:12:43,960
to better estimates down the line.

285
00:12:44,420 --> 00:12:45,861
And that's gonna help you with your scope planning.

286
00:12:46,862 --> 00:12:48,803
This can usually be like a producer's work,

287
00:12:48,843 --> 00:12:50,984
but as a lead, you can set a good example

288
00:12:51,364 --> 00:12:53,925
and send reminders to your team, put in your own estimates,

289
00:12:54,226 --> 00:12:55,566
just make sure everybody's doing it.

290
00:12:56,503 --> 00:12:58,885
And it doesn't have to be every five minutes

291
00:12:58,945 --> 00:12:59,906
or down to the minute.

292
00:12:59,926 --> 00:13:01,948
It can be kind of rough, like in hours,

293
00:13:02,028 --> 00:13:03,048
but it really does help.

294
00:13:05,070 --> 00:13:06,752
As I mentioned, we weren't great on God of War

295
00:13:06,772 --> 00:13:08,013
about collecting that data,

296
00:13:08,053 --> 00:13:09,454
so after the project was over,

297
00:13:09,514 --> 00:13:10,995
we went into Perforce,

298
00:13:11,476 --> 00:13:13,677
and we started looking at our Perforce history,

299
00:13:14,038 --> 00:13:15,279
just seeing when the dates were,

300
00:13:15,319 --> 00:13:16,460
when a file was checked in,

301
00:13:16,840 --> 00:13:18,281
seeing the notes of what people did

302
00:13:18,341 --> 00:13:20,063
when they did a certain scene,

303
00:13:20,563 --> 00:13:22,965
and we kind of took a sample set and tried to.

304
00:13:23,625 --> 00:13:27,807
take our best educated guess based on the revision history notes for how long it might

305
00:13:27,847 --> 00:13:28,728
have taken to do this.

306
00:13:29,468 --> 00:13:33,390
It wasn't super accurate, but it was still a better baseline than doing nothing.

307
00:13:33,930 --> 00:13:37,092
And now we have some rough estimates for planning out our next project.

308
00:13:39,473 --> 00:13:40,413
Beware of burnout.

309
00:13:41,314 --> 00:13:44,455
You know, it's one thing when you're only responsible for yourself and your own personal

310
00:13:44,475 --> 00:13:49,097
well-being and your health, but it's another thing when you have a team relying on you

311
00:13:49,617 --> 00:13:51,438
to establish a reasonable schedule and scope.

312
00:13:52,195 --> 00:13:54,376
So really keep an eye on the health and morale of your team.

313
00:13:55,316 --> 00:13:56,817
We had a pair of talented animators

314
00:13:57,117 --> 00:13:59,498
who kept staying up till one in the morning in the office,

315
00:13:59,758 --> 00:14:01,239
despite me telling them to go home.

316
00:14:02,039 --> 00:14:02,859
Well, whose fault was it?

317
00:14:03,139 --> 00:14:05,040
Were they just perfectionists, staying late,

318
00:14:05,060 --> 00:14:06,621
noodling on everything with all their passion?

319
00:14:07,581 --> 00:14:09,682
Or was it maybe that because they were so fast,

320
00:14:09,982 --> 00:14:11,443
I piled on too many tasks on them?

321
00:14:12,343 --> 00:14:13,944
Maybe if I'd had a better sense of the scope,

322
00:14:13,964 --> 00:14:16,005
we could have talked about cutting down their work a bit,

323
00:14:16,765 --> 00:14:17,846
or maybe hiring more people

324
00:14:18,106 --> 00:14:19,687
so that they could go home at a reasonable hour.

325
00:14:23,573 --> 00:14:25,414
The next thing in organization that helped me

326
00:14:25,474 --> 00:14:26,675
was just keeping tidy.

327
00:14:27,456 --> 00:14:28,797
And this was something I never thought about

328
00:14:28,817 --> 00:14:29,758
when I was in film school,

329
00:14:29,858 --> 00:14:31,479
learning how to use spreadsheets.

330
00:14:31,979 --> 00:14:32,160
Woo!

331
00:14:33,581 --> 00:14:34,241
But when you're a lead,

332
00:14:34,421 --> 00:14:36,223
learning some office software can really help you

333
00:14:36,283 --> 00:14:38,705
with asset lists, estimates, order forms,

334
00:14:38,945 --> 00:14:39,706
all that fun stuff.

335
00:14:40,406 --> 00:14:42,488
So take some time to learn something like Excel

336
00:14:42,648 --> 00:14:44,990
or Google Sheets, or whatever's gonna work best for you.

337
00:14:45,770 --> 00:14:48,192
A bonus is, as an artist, you can make them look pretty.

338
00:14:49,213 --> 00:14:49,433
That's fun.

339
00:14:53,907 --> 00:14:55,969
Documentation, super important.

340
00:14:56,910 --> 00:14:59,292
Take time to write down your team's best practices,

341
00:14:59,913 --> 00:15:02,475
your workflows, your tutorials, et cetera.

342
00:15:03,356 --> 00:15:05,779
This will, one, make it easier for new hires

343
00:15:05,819 --> 00:15:06,639
to hit the ground running,

344
00:15:07,320 --> 00:15:09,663
and also serve as a handy reference during crunch.

345
00:15:11,364 --> 00:15:12,565
When we were in the midst of production,

346
00:15:13,006 --> 00:15:14,287
the animators had something they called

347
00:15:14,327 --> 00:15:15,949
the buttery smooth checklist.

348
00:15:16,698 --> 00:15:18,380
Because we didn't have any cuts in God of War,

349
00:15:18,740 --> 00:15:20,401
we had to make sure that every animation

350
00:15:20,922 --> 00:15:23,324
traveled smoothly from gameplay into a cinematic

351
00:15:23,384 --> 00:15:23,904
and back out.

352
00:15:24,245 --> 00:15:25,285
And everything on this checklist,

353
00:15:25,306 --> 00:15:26,066
I mean, you don't have to read it,

354
00:15:26,346 --> 00:15:27,868
but it actually helped the animators

355
00:15:27,908 --> 00:15:29,169
before they exported anything

356
00:15:29,789 --> 00:15:31,210
to make sure that when they exported it

357
00:15:31,270 --> 00:15:32,171
and put it in the game engine,

358
00:15:32,191 --> 00:15:33,652
there was the least amount of pops

359
00:15:33,692 --> 00:15:34,853
and troubleshooting we had to do.

360
00:15:35,414 --> 00:15:37,976
This was very crucial to the success of our no-cut camera.

361
00:15:39,331 --> 00:15:41,472
All right, let's try a little organizational

362
00:15:41,532 --> 00:15:42,372
audience activity.

363
00:15:42,392 --> 00:15:45,514
I'm gonna ask you guys to do a little flow chart,

364
00:15:45,634 --> 00:15:48,095
a quick and dirty three-step workflow of your position.

365
00:15:49,356 --> 00:15:50,856
Where does your work come from?

366
00:15:51,697 --> 00:15:53,118
If there are any students, your work might come

367
00:15:53,138 --> 00:15:54,438
from a teacher or something like that.

368
00:15:55,499 --> 00:15:56,479
What work do you do?

369
00:15:58,060 --> 00:15:59,301
And who do you send your work to?

370
00:15:59,941 --> 00:16:02,802
For example, as an animator, I get my work

371
00:16:02,822 --> 00:16:04,163
from the writers, they give me the scripts.

372
00:16:04,643 --> 00:16:06,244
I talk with the level designers to figure out

373
00:16:06,264 --> 00:16:07,765
where my cinematic's going to take place.

374
00:16:08,592 --> 00:16:10,093
I work with my director of photography

375
00:16:10,133 --> 00:16:11,534
to figure out the staging of the scene,

376
00:16:12,134 --> 00:16:14,696
and then we shoot it, and then the animator takes it

377
00:16:14,736 --> 00:16:16,457
and assembles it all together and animates it

378
00:16:16,497 --> 00:16:17,357
and makes it look awesome.

379
00:16:18,278 --> 00:16:21,020
We then export that and send that to our implementation team.

380
00:16:21,260 --> 00:16:23,341
We send that to our lighting team, effects, and audio.

381
00:16:23,901 --> 00:16:25,522
I mean, this is a pretty generalized workflow,

382
00:16:25,542 --> 00:16:26,463
but you guys get the idea.

383
00:16:27,683 --> 00:16:29,625
So go ahead and make your own flowchart,

384
00:16:29,705 --> 00:16:31,326
and then share it with your new best friend

385
00:16:31,346 --> 00:16:32,486
and colleague sitting next to you.

386
00:16:34,888 --> 00:16:36,829
Some final takeaways about organization.

387
00:16:38,110 --> 00:16:39,291
Really, everything that you're doing

388
00:16:39,331 --> 00:16:40,712
is helping you get the big picture

389
00:16:40,732 --> 00:16:42,193
by understanding your flow,

390
00:16:42,353 --> 00:16:44,174
your place within the production process,

391
00:16:45,295 --> 00:16:46,896
and also learning just how much time

392
00:16:46,996 --> 00:16:49,979
each of those steps take, so you can run smoothly.

393
00:16:51,700 --> 00:16:53,842
On the cinematic team, we've charted out,

394
00:16:54,022 --> 00:16:56,263
like I mentioned, that was a general workflow,

395
00:16:56,283 --> 00:16:58,345
and this is really our full pipeline here,

396
00:16:59,206 --> 00:17:01,888
and it really looks scary, but what it's doing

397
00:17:01,928 --> 00:17:03,849
is it's helping us identify our handoffs

398
00:17:03,929 --> 00:17:05,130
between all the different departments.

399
00:17:05,903 --> 00:17:07,944
It's identifying any potential pain points

400
00:17:08,584 --> 00:17:11,206
and figuring out areas where we can work simultaneously

401
00:17:11,266 --> 00:17:13,447
across disciplines to save time, such as right here.

402
00:17:14,508 --> 00:17:16,889
So that's being really, that's really beneficial for us.

403
00:17:18,970 --> 00:17:20,351
I'd like to take a quick moment just to talk

404
00:17:20,371 --> 00:17:22,372
about outsourcing since this is becoming more

405
00:17:22,392 --> 00:17:24,233
and more common in AAA game studios.

406
00:17:24,893 --> 00:17:26,474
And it was definitely a skill that I had to learn

407
00:17:26,514 --> 00:17:27,895
on the fly as a first time lead.

408
00:17:28,815 --> 00:17:30,356
First up, get to know your vendors.

409
00:17:31,337 --> 00:17:32,357
Every studio is different.

410
00:17:33,058 --> 00:17:34,919
Some like to take your work and really run with it

411
00:17:34,959 --> 00:17:35,619
and get creative.

412
00:17:36,382 --> 00:17:38,444
Others prefer very specific direction from you

413
00:17:38,505 --> 00:17:41,367
so they can get their work done to your specific advice.

414
00:17:42,469 --> 00:17:44,351
Some are good at working at a variety of tasks,

415
00:17:44,811 --> 00:17:47,033
and others are more specialized little boutiques

416
00:17:47,053 --> 00:17:48,875
that are really good at doing one thing in particular.

417
00:17:49,936 --> 00:17:51,698
Some like to present their own schedules to you,

418
00:17:52,199 --> 00:17:54,701
and some prefer to work with you to establish timelines.

419
00:17:55,943 --> 00:17:57,104
So just get to know your vendors.

420
00:17:59,427 --> 00:18:02,570
Learn how to give very specific and detailed feedback

421
00:18:03,050 --> 00:18:05,392
because it can be harder to communicate across time zones

422
00:18:05,733 --> 00:18:06,773
and across different languages.

423
00:18:07,234 --> 00:18:10,176
So really use images, videos, Skype calls if possible.

424
00:18:10,717 --> 00:18:12,719
Here's an example of one of our outsourcing notes

425
00:18:12,739 --> 00:18:16,642
where we listed a very specific time frame and a note

426
00:18:17,042 --> 00:18:19,044
and drew on top of a still frame

427
00:18:19,064 --> 00:18:21,266
so people got a good idea of what we wanted from them.

428
00:18:24,557 --> 00:18:26,498
Also, time management becomes even more crucial

429
00:18:26,518 --> 00:18:27,618
when working with outsourcing.

430
00:18:28,118 --> 00:18:29,679
Because when you're dealing with your internal team,

431
00:18:29,699 --> 00:18:31,279
you sit next to them, you see them every day,

432
00:18:31,299 --> 00:18:32,439
it's cool, you're communicating.

433
00:18:32,860 --> 00:18:33,840
But with your outsource team,

434
00:18:33,880 --> 00:18:35,520
it can be easy to lose track of them.

435
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,261
You might forget to send your feedback in a timely manner.

436
00:18:39,742 --> 00:18:40,762
You might forget to check in

437
00:18:40,802 --> 00:18:42,202
and see if they're blocked by anything,

438
00:18:42,242 --> 00:18:44,023
if they have any roadblocks and they're stuck on work,

439
00:18:44,523 --> 00:18:46,343
and they might not have communicated with you.

440
00:18:47,463 --> 00:18:48,403
So don't leave them hanging.

441
00:18:48,543 --> 00:18:49,564
Make sure you keep track of them.

442
00:18:50,064 --> 00:18:52,406
What helped us was having an outsource coordinator

443
00:18:52,786 --> 00:18:55,007
because he really kept those lines of communication open,

444
00:18:55,387 --> 00:18:56,948
would give me reminders, would help make sure

445
00:18:56,988 --> 00:18:59,069
that our assets were sent out and come back

446
00:18:59,329 --> 00:19:00,510
in a nice, smooth manner.

447
00:19:00,790 --> 00:19:01,731
So he helped us a lot.

448
00:19:04,852 --> 00:19:06,653
All right, moving on to inspiration.

449
00:19:07,514 --> 00:19:09,115
This is all about keeping your team members

450
00:19:09,175 --> 00:19:10,155
motivated and growing.

451
00:19:10,996 --> 00:19:12,597
Probably not the way that Kratos does it.

452
00:19:14,177 --> 00:19:16,879
What you should do is be a source of positivity.

453
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:20,601
Because let's face it, stuff's gonna happen

454
00:19:21,041 --> 00:19:22,522
that there's gonna be decisions made

455
00:19:22,722 --> 00:19:24,882
that your team doesn't like, that you may not like.

456
00:19:25,642 --> 00:19:26,803
You may have to scrap some work.

457
00:19:27,163 --> 00:19:28,103
You may have to start over.

458
00:19:28,643 --> 00:19:30,324
There's gonna be tasks that nobody likes to do.

459
00:19:30,344 --> 00:19:32,584
There's gonna be things that make you just wanna rage out.

460
00:19:35,065 --> 00:19:37,626
But what happens is that your team members are watching you

461
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:39,746
and they're gonna gauge how you're feeling.

462
00:19:40,226 --> 00:19:41,787
So if they see that you're frustrated

463
00:19:42,007 --> 00:19:43,167
or worried or complaining,

464
00:19:43,867 --> 00:19:45,088
then they're gonna see that as permission

465
00:19:45,108 --> 00:19:45,808
to act out as well.

466
00:19:47,329 --> 00:19:48,570
So be a source of positivity.

467
00:19:49,811 --> 00:19:50,893
I know this is very cliche.

468
00:19:50,913 --> 00:19:52,674
I've actually already heard this a few times

469
00:19:52,714 --> 00:19:54,736
at this conference, but fake it till you make it.

470
00:19:55,457 --> 00:19:57,259
You know, it might seem disingenuous

471
00:19:57,299 --> 00:19:59,661
to put on a happy face when you're actually upset,

472
00:20:00,522 --> 00:20:01,803
but this really does go a long way

473
00:20:01,843 --> 00:20:03,404
to boosting your team's morale if they see

474
00:20:03,444 --> 00:20:05,847
that you're keeping pushing forward even under stress.

475
00:20:07,208 --> 00:20:09,830
It also can actually help prevent your own negativity

476
00:20:09,850 --> 00:20:12,253
from spiraling into something larger than it needs to be.

477
00:20:14,467 --> 00:20:16,088
Now, if you're really feeling upset,

478
00:20:16,108 --> 00:20:18,309
you just don't feel like you can hide it under a happy face,

479
00:20:18,349 --> 00:20:19,950
then find an outlet to let off your steam.

480
00:20:20,610 --> 00:20:22,131
You know, talk to your producers or managers,

481
00:20:22,191 --> 00:20:24,592
or just find a friend that you feel like

482
00:20:24,612 --> 00:20:26,833
you can talk to them about, and just let it out.

483
00:20:26,974 --> 00:20:28,294
Or find an activity to do.

484
00:20:29,355 --> 00:20:30,255
I like to sing in a choir.

485
00:20:31,256 --> 00:20:34,417
When I was at UCLA, our choir director's motto was,

486
00:20:34,737 --> 00:20:36,018
leave your baggage at the door.

487
00:20:36,698 --> 00:20:38,219
You might have had a worst day in the world,

488
00:20:38,239 --> 00:20:39,260
but when you come to rehearsal,

489
00:20:39,300 --> 00:20:40,260
you leave that at the doorway,

490
00:20:40,280 --> 00:20:42,641
and you come in, and you put on a smile, and you sing.

491
00:20:44,043 --> 00:20:46,745
Now, I mean, part of singing is that you're performers,

492
00:20:46,765 --> 00:20:49,327
you're acting, you know, so it might seem a little fake,

493
00:20:49,387 --> 00:20:50,428
but by the end of rehearsal,

494
00:20:50,548 --> 00:20:52,590
we actually were all genuinely feeling better,

495
00:20:52,630 --> 00:20:54,551
and we would leave with a genuine smile on our face.

496
00:20:54,631 --> 00:20:56,993
So having that outlet is very important.

497
00:21:00,456 --> 00:21:01,196
Ah, feedback.

498
00:21:01,517 --> 00:21:03,318
You could do a whole talk just on feedback.

499
00:21:03,338 --> 00:21:04,879
In fact, people have and are doing that.

500
00:21:06,180 --> 00:21:08,442
It falls under inspiration because giving good feedback

501
00:21:08,482 --> 00:21:10,103
can really help keep your team motivated.

502
00:21:12,450 --> 00:21:14,911
Something that's good for feedback

503
00:21:14,951 --> 00:21:15,891
is just getting to the point,

504
00:21:16,011 --> 00:21:17,672
because you are an expert in your field,

505
00:21:18,412 --> 00:21:19,952
and you are responsible for the end result

506
00:21:19,972 --> 00:21:21,313
being shipped to the rest of the world.

507
00:21:22,013 --> 00:21:23,994
So don't lose your feedback amongst too much fluff.

508
00:21:24,674 --> 00:21:26,255
Now as an animator, we love to use our bodies

509
00:21:26,295 --> 00:21:27,995
to demonstrate feedback, as you remember

510
00:21:28,015 --> 00:21:29,256
from the beginning of my slides.

511
00:21:30,036 --> 00:21:31,377
It's very direct and to the point.

512
00:21:31,957 --> 00:21:34,418
We even have a box full of prop weapons

513
00:21:34,518 --> 00:21:37,259
near our desks for very important research.

514
00:21:37,739 --> 00:21:37,919
Yes.

515
00:21:40,706 --> 00:21:43,128
Now, getting to the point means being honest,

516
00:21:43,188 --> 00:21:44,530
but not putting people down.

517
00:21:45,230 --> 00:21:47,833
Because again, your team is looking for someone

518
00:21:47,853 --> 00:21:48,894
they can turn to for help.

519
00:21:49,474 --> 00:21:51,576
And if they feel that you're just gonna yell at them

520
00:21:51,616 --> 00:21:52,657
or whatever when they come to you,

521
00:21:52,677 --> 00:21:54,078
then they're not going to come to you.

522
00:21:54,439 --> 00:21:55,880
And then how can you help them?

523
00:21:57,101 --> 00:21:57,942
So don't be belittling.

524
00:21:59,483 --> 00:22:00,144
Be encouraging.

525
00:22:03,703 --> 00:22:06,344
When you're in art school, you get graded on your work,

526
00:22:06,384 --> 00:22:07,825
and if you do really well, you get an A,

527
00:22:07,845 --> 00:22:08,866
and that feels awesome.

528
00:22:09,806 --> 00:22:11,407
And in the studio setting, it can be harder

529
00:22:11,427 --> 00:22:13,648
to come across that kind of positive reinforcement.

530
00:22:13,828 --> 00:22:16,049
So make sure you call out the good stuff,

531
00:22:16,670 --> 00:22:18,891
especially for your young people who are just out of school

532
00:22:19,511 --> 00:22:21,632
and may be struggling to adapt to the work environment.

533
00:22:22,866 --> 00:22:25,507
On God of War, we had an intern who, during reviews,

534
00:22:25,527 --> 00:22:26,947
would end up getting a lot more notes

535
00:22:27,047 --> 00:22:28,728
just because he needed more experience.

536
00:22:29,508 --> 00:22:31,468
But I always made sure to point out what he did well

537
00:22:31,668 --> 00:22:32,889
and gave him lots of encouragement.

538
00:22:33,649 --> 00:22:35,710
And he ended up taking on some of the most ambitious scenes

539
00:22:35,750 --> 00:22:38,370
on our project and just did an amazing job.

540
00:22:38,550 --> 00:22:39,491
So that was awesome.

541
00:22:42,031 --> 00:22:42,872
Finally, follow-up.

542
00:22:43,472 --> 00:22:44,692
Some artists can be introverted.

543
00:22:44,812 --> 00:22:45,872
I mean, that's why they're artists.

544
00:22:45,892 --> 00:22:47,673
They want to express themselves through their art

545
00:22:48,113 --> 00:22:48,993
and not talk about it.

546
00:22:50,021 --> 00:22:51,601
So just stop by their desk,

547
00:22:51,741 --> 00:22:53,082
make sure they're going in the right direction,

548
00:22:53,122 --> 00:22:54,602
and let them know that you're there for them.

549
00:22:55,222 --> 00:22:56,682
Let them know that they can ask questions,

550
00:22:57,102 --> 00:22:58,223
they can give their own opinions,

551
00:22:58,263 --> 00:22:59,823
and you will be a good listener and listen to them.

552
00:23:02,763 --> 00:23:04,484
And don't forget to request feedback, too.

553
00:23:05,164 --> 00:23:06,524
Especially as a first-time lead,

554
00:23:06,704 --> 00:23:09,125
you probably have very little idea how effective you're being.

555
00:23:10,065 --> 00:23:12,065
It can feel kind of awkward asking for advice,

556
00:23:12,505 --> 00:23:14,486
but it's important to get your team to be honest with you.

557
00:23:15,206 --> 00:23:16,946
You can show them that you care about them enough

558
00:23:17,106 --> 00:23:17,746
to want to be better.

559
00:23:18,719 --> 00:23:20,641
You can also talk to your producers or managers

560
00:23:20,781 --> 00:23:22,022
and see how you're doing from them.

561
00:23:22,782 --> 00:23:25,504
This is really about inspiring yourself to keep growing.

562
00:23:26,365 --> 00:23:28,266
Now this is a little scene from God of War,

563
00:23:28,306 --> 00:23:29,747
probably the only time in the game

564
00:23:29,787 --> 00:23:31,288
where Kratos asked for advice.

565
00:23:31,308 --> 00:23:33,150
I'm gonna go ahead and play that video for you.

566
00:23:34,631 --> 00:23:37,173
I mean, I get angry at you sometimes, but.

567
00:23:37,313 --> 00:23:37,813
Do you?

568
00:23:38,554 --> 00:23:41,396
I mean, sometimes, yeah, a little.

569
00:23:41,416 --> 00:23:44,378
When are you angry?

570
00:23:45,219 --> 00:23:45,399
What?

571
00:23:45,879 --> 00:23:46,320
With me.

572
00:23:48,582 --> 00:23:54,688
Oh, I guess sometimes when you don't think I can do something, but I can.

573
00:23:56,149 --> 00:24:00,593
You see Kratos asked his son for advice, like, when do you get angry with me?

574
00:24:00,673 --> 00:24:01,994
Why, why am I making you angry?

575
00:24:02,054 --> 00:24:02,334
You know?

576
00:24:02,714 --> 00:24:06,257
And if he hadn't asked, then he wouldn't have known how his son is trying so hard

577
00:24:06,297 --> 00:24:09,600
to prove himself to his father, to show that he is grown up enough and he can

578
00:24:09,640 --> 00:24:10,881
handle some more responsibility.

579
00:24:11,462 --> 00:24:14,084
So that was really cool moment that I thought was cool.

580
00:24:16,921 --> 00:24:20,704
So remember that artists come in all different kinds.

581
00:24:21,024 --> 00:24:23,365
This is our animation team, pretty diverse.

582
00:24:24,026 --> 00:24:26,468
And understanding what they love to do

583
00:24:27,368 --> 00:24:29,430
lets you let them work on what they're passionate about.

584
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:31,511
So give them what they wanna work on.

585
00:24:32,612 --> 00:24:34,513
But also remember to push them out of their comfort zone

586
00:24:34,533 --> 00:24:35,934
because that's really gonna help them grow.

587
00:24:35,954 --> 00:24:38,456
Okay, I'm not gonna make you guys

588
00:24:38,496 --> 00:24:39,577
do an activity right now.

589
00:24:39,617 --> 00:24:41,018
This is more of a take home test.

590
00:24:42,897 --> 00:24:44,097
called Inspire Your Team.

591
00:24:44,297 --> 00:24:46,477
I'm gonna give you kind of a role-playing scenario

592
00:24:46,497 --> 00:24:47,737
where you have a team of artists,

593
00:24:48,278 --> 00:24:49,658
and your job is to keep them happy

594
00:24:50,058 --> 00:24:51,498
and figure out ways to challenge them

595
00:24:51,518 --> 00:24:52,298
and keep them growing.

596
00:24:53,638 --> 00:24:55,459
Your first team member is a scrappy new kid,

597
00:24:55,819 --> 00:24:57,739
fresh out of school, ready to soak up information

598
00:24:57,759 --> 00:24:59,960
like a sponge, and needs more experience.

599
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:02,800
Then you've got your seasoned veteran,

600
00:25:03,260 --> 00:25:05,120
those game people who've been in the trenches

601
00:25:05,161 --> 00:25:06,721
for over a decade, they know all the ropes,

602
00:25:07,181 --> 00:25:08,421
maybe they're a little bit jaded, you know,

603
00:25:08,461 --> 00:25:09,901
but they wanna do the work.

604
00:25:09,981 --> 00:25:10,741
They're in it to win it.

605
00:25:13,004 --> 00:25:16,947
You've got that super fast insomniac who comes fresh from another AAA studio,

606
00:25:17,007 --> 00:25:20,350
is really fast cranking out assets, but ends up working themselves to the bone

607
00:25:20,370 --> 00:25:22,352
and refuse to go home even at one in the morning.

608
00:25:23,132 --> 00:25:24,353
How do you keep these people happy?

609
00:25:24,854 --> 00:25:25,854
How do you challenge them?

610
00:25:27,456 --> 00:25:29,597
How about someone who comes from film or television?

611
00:25:30,098 --> 00:25:30,979
They're super good.

612
00:25:30,999 --> 00:25:34,481
Their stuff is such high quality and they give great feedback to everybody,

613
00:25:35,142 --> 00:25:37,724
but maybe they've got some extra difficulty working with the game engine.

614
00:25:39,855 --> 00:25:42,156
Your final team member is an indie jack of all trades.

615
00:25:42,337 --> 00:25:43,417
Maybe they came from commercials,

616
00:25:43,877 --> 00:25:44,958
maybe they came from indie games.

617
00:25:45,398 --> 00:25:46,659
They know a little bit about everything,

618
00:25:46,699 --> 00:25:48,059
they love wearing lots of different hats,

619
00:25:48,420 --> 00:25:49,960
they love to branch out and experiment,

620
00:25:50,381 --> 00:25:52,462
but maybe they lack a little bit of polish and focus.

621
00:25:53,242 --> 00:25:55,623
This is your team, so do a little bit of role playing

622
00:25:55,643 --> 00:25:57,944
and think about how you might help them,

623
00:25:58,024 --> 00:25:59,365
keep them happy and help them grow.

624
00:25:59,385 --> 00:26:02,747
I'll leave this up here for just a second

625
00:26:02,787 --> 00:26:03,667
in case you wanna write it down.

626
00:26:09,849 --> 00:26:10,149
All right.

627
00:26:11,250 --> 00:26:14,134
Inspiration is really about learning to speak

628
00:26:14,194 --> 00:26:15,435
each of your teammates' language.

629
00:26:16,016 --> 00:26:17,217
Everybody thinks differently.

630
00:26:17,958 --> 00:26:20,401
So if you can figure out how your team members think,

631
00:26:20,962 --> 00:26:23,585
you can help them stay motivated and happy.

632
00:26:24,927 --> 00:26:27,830
You can tailor your feedback and help them stay motivated.

633
00:26:28,650 --> 00:26:34,053
On God of War we had a series of meaty scenes, cinematics featuring stunts and big creatures,

634
00:26:34,393 --> 00:26:36,874
all that cool stuff that animators love to get their hands into.

635
00:26:37,675 --> 00:26:40,036
My task was spreading them out amongst my team.

636
00:26:40,416 --> 00:26:43,117
So I would go to each of them and ask them what they wanted to work on.

637
00:26:43,577 --> 00:26:45,959
while also keeping in mind their experience levels,

638
00:26:46,399 --> 00:26:48,501
their speed, what they're passionate about,

639
00:26:48,981 --> 00:26:50,302
and made sure that in the end,

640
00:26:50,643 --> 00:26:52,624
everybody got at least one big meaty scene.

641
00:26:53,345 --> 00:26:54,445
That helped keep them happy,

642
00:26:54,625 --> 00:26:56,167
and it also helped keep my schedule happy

643
00:26:56,207 --> 00:26:57,848
because I wasn't piling all the big scenes

644
00:26:57,888 --> 00:26:58,648
onto one animator.

645
00:27:02,771 --> 00:27:04,193
All right, accountability.

646
00:27:06,114 --> 00:27:08,736
This is about taking ownership of your impact

647
00:27:09,016 --> 00:27:11,978
on your team and on your team's impact on the game.

648
00:27:14,223 --> 00:27:17,065
Because the decisions that you make affect other people.

649
00:27:17,645 --> 00:27:19,886
They affect your teammates, they affect other departments.

650
00:27:20,546 --> 00:27:22,066
Especially your downstream departments.

651
00:27:22,607 --> 00:27:24,187
So make sure you always keep them in the loop.

652
00:27:24,527 --> 00:27:26,148
That's getting back to communication again.

653
00:27:26,968 --> 00:27:29,349
Here I'm speaking to our dialogue coordinator, Leilani.

654
00:27:30,129 --> 00:27:32,450
Audio is actually a very important downstream department

655
00:27:32,470 --> 00:27:34,771
for cinematics, so we need to make sure

656
00:27:34,811 --> 00:27:36,432
they always had what they needed from us.

657
00:27:36,912 --> 00:27:39,113
Most often it was just play blasts of our cinematics

658
00:27:39,153 --> 00:27:40,854
with the time frames or the time code on it

659
00:27:40,874 --> 00:27:42,254
so they could properly sync up the sound.

660
00:27:43,198 --> 00:27:44,779
but keep your downstream departments in the loop.

661
00:27:48,462 --> 00:27:49,542
Set the bar for quality.

662
00:27:50,703 --> 00:27:52,585
You've trained your whole career to know what looks good,

663
00:27:53,285 --> 00:27:54,846
so make sure you can set expectations

664
00:27:54,906 --> 00:27:56,227
for what you want from your team.

665
00:27:57,188 --> 00:27:59,429
Because when your team understands what's high quality,

666
00:27:59,549 --> 00:28:00,390
what you want from them,

667
00:28:00,930 --> 00:28:02,692
that helps them function more autonomously,

668
00:28:02,912 --> 00:28:04,693
that helps them take ownership of their own stuff,

669
00:28:05,274 --> 00:28:06,735
and that helps your team run more smoothly,

670
00:28:07,135 --> 00:28:09,336
even if you have to step away, like I did.

671
00:28:11,335 --> 00:28:16,519
I went on maternity leave right before alpha, which is probably the worst time in the world

672
00:28:16,579 --> 00:28:19,762
to have a baby while you're trying to wrap up your game development.

673
00:28:20,823 --> 00:28:26,247
But what I did was I met with all my producers and my senior animators and discussed how

674
00:28:26,287 --> 00:28:27,869
I was going to hand off all my stuff.

675
00:28:29,050 --> 00:28:33,333
I wrote up some detailed current state documents for all of my unfinished work to help transition

676
00:28:33,754 --> 00:28:35,235
all of those scenes off to other owners.

677
00:28:36,256 --> 00:28:38,457
And I was able to step back in after a few months

678
00:28:38,837 --> 00:28:41,338
and see that work had progressed pretty well while I was gone.

679
00:28:42,399 --> 00:28:44,920
In fact, later on in production, when one of my contractors

680
00:28:44,960 --> 00:28:48,042
had to leave midway, he ended up doing the same thing for me.

681
00:28:48,862 --> 00:28:51,063
He gave me a detailed current state document

682
00:28:51,083 --> 00:28:52,324
for each of his unfinished scenes

683
00:28:52,704 --> 00:28:54,785
so that I could make a smooth transition handing it off

684
00:28:54,805 --> 00:28:55,765
to other owners.

685
00:28:56,065 --> 00:28:58,006
So that was a nice, warm, fuzzy feeling.

686
00:29:02,428 --> 00:29:03,449
Yeah, accountability.

687
00:29:04,612 --> 00:29:07,234
Nobody's perfect, but don't sweat it, you know.

688
00:29:07,615 --> 00:29:09,536
But do talk to people, own up if you mess up.

689
00:29:10,457 --> 00:29:11,638
And work to fix the problem.

690
00:29:12,599 --> 00:29:14,340
Your team members will respect your honesty

691
00:29:14,540 --> 00:29:15,801
and your commitment to grow with them.

692
00:29:16,862 --> 00:29:17,683
But don't dwell on it.

693
00:29:17,923 --> 00:29:19,424
I mean, most times people,

694
00:29:20,045 --> 00:29:21,786
everyone else will have moved on before you.

695
00:29:22,207 --> 00:29:24,449
So don't let it eat you up inside, really just let it out.

696
00:29:24,749 --> 00:29:26,270
Like when you make a crappy drawing,

697
00:29:26,690 --> 00:29:28,652
just toss it out and move on to the next one

698
00:29:28,672 --> 00:29:29,533
so you can get to the good stuff.

699
00:29:33,290 --> 00:29:35,511
Part of accountability is also making sure

700
00:29:35,531 --> 00:29:37,913
that your voice is heard and your team's voice is heard

701
00:29:38,033 --> 00:29:38,873
since you represent them.

702
00:29:40,374 --> 00:29:42,295
Now we know, artists are usually the cool kids

703
00:29:42,335 --> 00:29:44,416
in the back of the room doodling on their notebooks.

704
00:29:45,256 --> 00:29:47,438
But as a lead, you don't wanna sit in the back.

705
00:29:48,678 --> 00:29:49,739
So take a seat at the table.

706
00:29:51,239 --> 00:29:52,580
Don't let other people make decisions

707
00:29:52,620 --> 00:29:53,961
that affect you and your team

708
00:29:53,981 --> 00:29:55,302
without your opinion being heard.

709
00:29:55,942 --> 00:29:56,622
So be visible.

710
00:29:58,963 --> 00:30:00,124
Come prepared to those meetings.

711
00:30:01,252 --> 00:30:03,174
Be aware of the subject matter, make notes,

712
00:30:03,994 --> 00:30:06,136
bring questions, be an active participant.

713
00:30:07,316 --> 00:30:09,738
This has the benefit of making those meetings more engaging

714
00:30:10,599 --> 00:30:12,540
and then you don't get bored and start watching the clock

715
00:30:12,560 --> 00:30:14,181
and start doodling your sketchbooks or whatever.

716
00:30:17,223 --> 00:30:18,324
Go to bat for your team.

717
00:30:19,184 --> 00:30:20,725
Remember, your team members are counting on you

718
00:30:20,746 --> 00:30:21,466
to represent them.

719
00:30:22,307 --> 00:30:23,708
So make sure that you get what you need

720
00:30:23,748 --> 00:30:25,229
for your team to work well from others

721
00:30:26,129 --> 00:30:27,630
and give back to the other departments as well.

722
00:30:30,567 --> 00:30:32,668
This is a little bit more of an introspective exercise

723
00:30:32,708 --> 00:30:33,649
you can do on your own time.

724
00:30:33,829 --> 00:30:35,710
Sort of a personal accountability checkup.

725
00:30:37,310 --> 00:30:39,571
First off, pledge to speak up at meetings.

726
00:30:39,932 --> 00:30:41,812
Like actually take out your calendar,

727
00:30:42,353 --> 00:30:43,473
find out when your next meeting is,

728
00:30:43,873 --> 00:30:44,794
and write down that pledge.

729
00:30:44,814 --> 00:30:45,794
Like really write it out.

730
00:30:45,954 --> 00:30:49,076
I pledge to speak up at this tech art meeting

731
00:30:49,556 --> 00:30:50,497
and maybe take some notes,

732
00:30:50,517 --> 00:30:51,537
like what am I gonna say at it,

733
00:30:51,577 --> 00:30:52,497
what questions am I gonna ask?

734
00:30:52,517 --> 00:30:53,138
Like make a pledge.

735
00:30:56,791 --> 00:31:00,132
If you haven't synced up with your downstream departments in a while, set a date to sync

736
00:31:00,152 --> 00:31:00,432
with them.

737
00:31:01,553 --> 00:31:04,774
Ask them what you can do to help make their jobs easier.

738
00:31:07,775 --> 00:31:12,437
Finally, write down a name or two of people that you maybe need to own up to.

739
00:31:13,297 --> 00:31:14,577
Some you want to talk to one-on-one.

740
00:31:15,498 --> 00:31:16,638
Figure out when you can schedule it.

741
00:31:16,858 --> 00:31:20,339
It could just be like a casual walk around the parking lot or a coffee break or something,

742
00:31:20,380 --> 00:31:21,680
but you know, be open.

743
00:31:21,920 --> 00:31:22,460
Take some time.

744
00:31:25,498 --> 00:31:28,060
Remember that when you are accountable to others,

745
00:31:28,741 --> 00:31:29,802
they will be accountable to you.

746
00:31:30,242 --> 00:31:31,243
That old golden rule.

747
00:31:34,686 --> 00:31:37,848
Finally, and perhaps most importantly as artists,

748
00:31:38,088 --> 00:31:38,749
creativity.

749
00:31:39,910 --> 00:31:41,831
This is all about finding that delicate balance

750
00:31:41,871 --> 00:31:44,273
between all that leadership stuff we've been talking about

751
00:31:44,313 --> 00:31:45,234
throughout this whole session,

752
00:31:46,014 --> 00:31:47,756
and finding time to do what you've trained for

753
00:31:47,776 --> 00:31:49,037
your whole life as an artist.

754
00:31:50,097 --> 00:31:53,240
Of course, don't try to do everything yourself.

755
00:31:54,226 --> 00:31:59,067
It's tempting to think of lead artists being able to solve all the biggest problems, doing

756
00:31:59,147 --> 00:32:01,867
all the biggest art tasks, taking everything on yourself.

757
00:32:02,948 --> 00:32:03,448
Just don't.

758
00:32:03,468 --> 00:32:07,929
You're going to be overwhelmed with the sheer amount of work to be done, and you'll have

759
00:32:07,989 --> 00:32:10,329
no time to achieve that high-quality bar that you want to set.

760
00:32:11,649 --> 00:32:15,230
You might get so bogged down in leadership stuff that you have no time to work on art

761
00:32:15,270 --> 00:32:15,610
at all.

762
00:32:17,050 --> 00:32:21,751
Or conversely, you might be focusing so hard on doing really good art that you're letting

763
00:32:21,771 --> 00:32:23,292
your team down and not being a good lead.

764
00:32:25,013 --> 00:32:25,634
So get some help.

765
00:32:26,334 --> 00:32:28,356
Let your producers or managers or other leads

766
00:32:28,416 --> 00:32:29,717
help you out and give you advice.

767
00:32:32,839 --> 00:32:34,661
Remember to trust your team to take ownership

768
00:32:34,781 --> 00:32:36,822
so that everyone else gets a chance to shine as well.

769
00:32:37,963 --> 00:32:39,825
Art school is really about honing your skills

770
00:32:39,865 --> 00:32:41,326
and becoming a master of your craft,

771
00:32:41,846 --> 00:32:43,808
while leadership is about helping others

772
00:32:43,848 --> 00:32:44,688
unlock their potential.

773
00:32:46,910 --> 00:32:50,333
That being said, do take some time for yourself.

774
00:32:51,352 --> 00:32:52,634
because you are still an artist.

