00:43:48,538 --> 00:43:49,358
My name is Shannon.

1033
00:43:49,538 --> 00:43:49,978
Hi, Shannon.

1034
00:43:50,238 --> 00:43:55,040
I was wondering, what are some ways that you evaluate your own success as a leader and

1035
00:43:55,080 --> 00:43:55,460
manager?

1036
00:43:56,480 --> 00:43:58,161
How do I evaluate my own success?

1037
00:44:00,058 --> 00:44:04,019
I think for me, the best part, well, at the end of each project, we do a post-mortem.

1038
00:44:04,559 --> 00:44:08,560
So that's when I tell them, hey guys, write down everything that went well and everything

1039
00:44:08,600 --> 00:44:11,620
that did not go well, and let's talk about it and figure it out.

1040
00:44:12,380 --> 00:44:15,841
And I try to get them to stay honest and give me that feedback.

1041
00:44:16,041 --> 00:44:21,802
And what really helped me feel good was at the end, some of my contractors, as they were

1042
00:44:21,842 --> 00:44:23,323
leaving, they said, hey, you were a really good lead.

1043
00:44:23,843 --> 00:44:25,043
Sometimes it's as simple as that.

1044
00:44:25,063 --> 00:44:27,163
Just someone coming up and saying, hey, you did a good job.

1045
00:44:27,665 --> 00:44:29,946
So I think that's important to also say to other people,

1046
00:44:29,986 --> 00:44:31,646
is telling them that they did a good job too.

1047
00:44:32,627 --> 00:44:32,947
Thank you.

1048
00:44:35,908 --> 00:44:37,468
Hi, thank you for the talk.

1049
00:44:37,928 --> 00:44:38,348
I'm Miguel.

1050
00:44:38,789 --> 00:44:38,969
Hi.

1051
00:44:39,449 --> 00:44:42,370
And my question is, when there are too many ideas

1052
00:44:42,430 --> 00:44:45,471
on the table, more or less, how do you coordinate

1053
00:44:45,491 --> 00:44:48,932
so that the amount of information overload

1054
00:44:49,452 --> 00:44:52,633
actually does not bog down the production of the project?

1055
00:44:52,653 --> 00:44:53,693
For example, there are many ideas

1056
00:44:53,733 --> 00:44:55,333
of how things should move or something.

1057
00:44:55,993 --> 00:44:58,656
Like, how do you just condense everything

1058
00:44:58,696 --> 00:45:00,779
into just getting to one solution?

1059
00:45:01,960 --> 00:45:02,801
Let me see if I understand.

1060
00:45:02,961 --> 00:45:05,845
You're wondering, when there's too many ideas on the table,

1061
00:45:05,925 --> 00:45:07,707
how do you make sure that you can move forward

1062
00:45:07,747 --> 00:45:09,028
in a right pace and everything?

1063
00:45:10,129 --> 00:45:14,572
I think when you're in a meeting, just setting goals for yourself like this is a one-hour

1064
00:45:14,613 --> 00:45:17,675
meeting, let's throw everything on the table, but by the end of the hour, we should narrow

1065
00:45:17,695 --> 00:45:19,836
it down to what we really need going forward.

1066
00:45:20,957 --> 00:45:24,100
Or if it's something where everybody's emailing each other back and forth, I know you should

1067
00:45:24,120 --> 00:45:25,601
do it like this, I know you should do it like that.

1068
00:45:25,921 --> 00:45:30,064
I mean, that's where, as a lead, you have the authority to step in and say, okay, we're

1069
00:45:30,084 --> 00:45:30,905
going to nail this down.

1070
00:45:31,625 --> 00:45:34,227
Maybe I'll talk about it with the other leads and I'll get back to you guys.

1071
00:45:34,367 --> 00:45:35,889
You know, it doesn't have to end right here.

1072
00:45:35,949 --> 00:45:36,389
We can...

1073
00:45:37,393 --> 00:45:38,934
We'll make the decision and let you guys know.

1074
00:45:38,954 --> 00:45:41,215
I mean, sometimes you can pull rank like that.

1075
00:45:42,515 --> 00:45:43,416
Okay, thank you.

1076
00:45:45,297 --> 00:45:45,597
Hello.

1077
00:45:46,157 --> 00:45:46,917
Hi.

1078
00:45:47,077 --> 00:45:49,819
So, let's say you have a person under you.

1079
00:45:51,099 --> 00:45:53,640
And I mean, of course, game is about reiteration, right?

1080
00:45:54,181 --> 00:45:56,782
So how if you've given a task to somebody below you,

1081
00:45:56,942 --> 00:45:59,803
and then after several reiteration and critique,

1082
00:46:00,444 --> 00:46:02,364
the work is still really off the mark,

1083
00:46:02,605 --> 00:46:05,506
and the time is running out, so what do you do?

1084
00:46:06,674 --> 00:46:07,414
That is a tough one.

1085
00:46:07,734 --> 00:46:10,755
What do you do when someone's reiterated time and time again

1086
00:46:10,775 --> 00:46:12,756
and it just isn't quite hitting the quality bar?

1087
00:46:13,796 --> 00:46:16,517
I think, first of all, you have to acknowledge the work

1088
00:46:16,557 --> 00:46:17,718
that they have put in so far.

1089
00:46:17,898 --> 00:46:19,218
So make sure you let them know,

1090
00:46:19,238 --> 00:46:20,919
I appreciate all the work you've put in.

1091
00:46:20,939 --> 00:46:22,659
I feel like at this point,

1092
00:46:22,899 --> 00:46:25,000
we should talk about other directions we can go.

1093
00:46:25,440 --> 00:46:26,941
And maybe you're just very tired

1094
00:46:26,961 --> 00:46:28,601
and let's see if we can put you on another task

1095
00:46:28,641 --> 00:46:30,622
and maybe get those creative juices flowing again.

1096
00:46:31,322 --> 00:46:32,562
Maybe we'll pass this off to someone,

1097
00:46:32,582 --> 00:46:33,783
just have them quickly wrap it up.

1098
00:46:34,193 --> 00:46:36,075
and get you working on something new that, you know,

1099
00:46:36,095 --> 00:46:38,217
I'm sure you're tired of doing it six times,

1100
00:46:38,597 --> 00:46:39,719
you know, let's give you something new

1101
00:46:39,759 --> 00:46:40,479
to challenge yourself.

1102
00:46:41,180 --> 00:46:41,681
Okay, thank you.

1103
00:46:44,788 --> 00:46:45,369
Are we good?

1104
00:46:45,389 --> 00:46:47,130
Not one more, okay.

1105
00:46:47,730 --> 00:46:47,990
Hi.

1106
00:46:48,150 --> 00:46:48,391
Hi.

1107
00:46:48,431 --> 00:46:49,471
Two small questions.

1108
00:46:49,992 --> 00:46:53,033
First one, what the amount of artists

1109
00:46:53,093 --> 00:46:56,195
you consider healthy in your team

1110
00:46:56,255 --> 00:46:58,157
to keep the balance you talked about?

1111
00:46:58,637 --> 00:47:01,098
Like to be a manager and to keep,

1112
00:47:01,579 --> 00:47:04,280
you know, looking new stuff in the industry.

1113
00:47:05,355 --> 00:47:09,078
Oh man, what do you consider like a good team size to lead?

1114
00:47:09,218 --> 00:47:11,780
So for example, five artists is okay.

1115
00:47:12,761 --> 00:47:14,442
Actually, I think five is pretty good.

1116
00:47:14,462 --> 00:47:16,043
You know, I was just at a talk where they were talking

1117
00:47:16,083 --> 00:47:18,385
about a study that was done about ideal team size

1118
00:47:18,425 --> 00:47:19,766
and I think the study said 4.6 people.

1119
00:47:22,635 --> 00:47:27,358
At the peak of production, I had seven animators under me, and it was a little tough.

1120
00:47:27,378 --> 00:47:31,421
I think five would have been nice, but I think I was able to get to seven.

1121
00:47:31,501 --> 00:47:36,545
It really is about how you manage your time, and if you feel like you can handle scheduling

1122
00:47:36,585 --> 00:47:38,446
enough time to get to each person individually.

1123
00:47:38,906 --> 00:47:40,667
then I think you're doing a good job.

1124
00:47:40,687 --> 00:47:43,447
But it's really about seeing how underwater you feel

1125
00:47:44,047 --> 00:47:45,848
for the amount of team that you have.

1126
00:47:46,368 --> 00:47:47,548
Depends on the project as well.

1127
00:47:47,908 --> 00:47:48,589
Okay, thanks.

1128
00:47:48,829 --> 00:47:53,590
And the second one, what if you have a batch of work

1129
00:47:53,930 --> 00:47:58,191
not interesting, like fixing bugs, for example,

1130
00:47:58,311 --> 00:48:01,372
from outsourcers, and you have a great team

1131
00:48:01,572 --> 00:48:04,893
of different specialists, skilled offshore,

1132
00:48:06,535 --> 00:48:09,928
So how would you how would you motivate them?

1133
00:48:11,060 --> 00:48:15,984
The question was, what do you do when you get tasks that is not very interesting and

1134
00:48:16,004 --> 00:48:18,986
you have a bunch of specialists that you want to make sure that they're happy?

1135
00:48:19,687 --> 00:48:24,510
For me, if it's a big task, rather than trying to take someone down for a long time, I might

1136
00:48:24,590 --> 00:48:28,674
say, okay, everybody, we're going to do this bug fixing, everybody take five bugs and let's

1137
00:48:28,694 --> 00:48:30,295
just get it out of the way as quickly as we can.

1138
00:48:30,495 --> 00:48:34,398
That whole many hands make light work thing, because then everybody's in it together, everybody

1139
00:48:34,438 --> 00:48:36,200
can kind of complain to each other and then say...

1140
00:48:37,015 --> 00:48:38,116
Oh, I've got to do bugs.

1141
00:48:38,156 --> 00:48:39,717
But then everybody gets done at the same time,

1142
00:48:39,757 --> 00:48:41,619
and then we can move on to the next fun thing.

1143
00:48:41,639 --> 00:48:43,660
OK, thanks a lot.

1144
00:48:43,800 --> 00:48:44,140
Thank you.

1145
00:48:47,543 --> 00:48:49,525
All right, if there's no further questions,

1146
00:48:49,605 --> 00:48:51,166
I'd just like to do a quick plug.

1147
00:48:51,646 --> 00:48:54,548
We have a couple of cinematic-related talks

1148
00:48:54,588 --> 00:48:55,369
coming up this week.

1149
00:48:55,429 --> 00:48:57,130
First on Wednesday, Doria Razzi is

1150
00:48:57,170 --> 00:49:00,413
giving a talk called Creating a Deeper Emotional Connection,

1151
00:49:00,613 --> 00:49:02,054
the Cinematography of God of War.

1152
00:49:02,074 --> 00:49:03,655
And that's going to be a really deep dive into.

1153
00:49:04,155 --> 00:49:06,977
the staging and composition and cinematography for our cut scenes.

1154
00:49:07,557 --> 00:49:10,619
And on Thursday I'm giving a talk called Keyframes and Cardboard Props,

1155
00:49:10,839 --> 00:49:14,921
the cinematic process behind God of War, and that'll be just kind of an overview

1156
00:49:14,961 --> 00:49:17,803
of everything from script all the way to screen, everything that we went through

1157
00:49:18,183 --> 00:49:20,324
to make sure that our cinematics worked with no cuts.

1158
00:49:21,424 --> 00:49:22,525
Thank you again very much.

